comprehensive characterization<br />of a waveguide balanced phonon-cooled NbN hot electron<br />bolometer (HEB) mixer on aGaNbuffer-layer operating at approximately<br />1.3 terahertz (THz). The measured uncorrected double<br />sideband noise temperature was as low as 750 K at 1 GHz<br />intermediate frequency (IF) and 900 K at 4 GHz IF, respectively,<br />and suggests a noise bandwidth of 7 GHz. Moreover, the IF gain<br />bandwidth of the HEB itself was deduced from a mixing experiment<br />with a second monochromatic THz signal source and has<br />shown a 3 dB roll-off at 5.5 GHz. The contribution of the HEB<br />mixer on the overall receiver noise temperature was determined<br />to be in the order of 300 K or 5 hf/k considering losses in the<br />RF transmission path and the waveguide components as well as<br />accounting for the receiver conversion loss, which was deduced<br />from the U-factor method. The achieved performance sets a new<br />benchmark for futureTHz instruments and emphasizes the technological<br />readiness of waveguide-based NbN HEB mixers employing<br />a GaN buffer-layer featuring significantly improved IF bandwidth<br />without compromising on the receiver’s noise comprehensive characterization<br />of a waveguide balanced phonon-cooled NbN hot electron<br />bolometer (HEB) mixer on aGaNbuffer-layer operating at approximately<br />1.3 terahertz (THz). The measured uncorrected double<br />sideband noise temperature was as low as 750 K at 1 GHz<br />intermediate frequency (IF) and 900 K at 4 GHz IF, respectively,<br />and suggests a noise bandwidth of 7 GHz. Moreover, the IF gain<br />bandwidth of the HEB itself was deduced from a mixing experiment<br />with a second monochromatic THz signal source and has<br />shown a 3 dB roll-off at 5.5 GHz. The contribution of the HEB<br />mixer on the overall receiver noise temperature was determined<br />to be in the order of 300 K or 5 hf/k considering losses in the<br />RF transmission path and the waveguide components as well as<br />accounting for the receiver conversion loss, which was deduced<br />from the U-factor method. The achieved performance sets a new<br />benchmark for futureTHz instruments and emphasizes the technological<br />readiness of waveguide-based NbN HEB mixers employing<br />a GaN buffer-layer featuring significantly improved IF bandwidth<br />without compromising on the receiver’s noise The contribution of the HEB<br />mixer on the overall receiver noise temperature was determined<br />to be in the order of 300 K or 5 hf/k considering losses in the<br />RF transmission path and the waveguide components as well as<br />accounting for the receiver conversion loss, which was deduced<br />from the U-factor method. The achieved performance sets a new<br />benchmark for futureTHz instruments and emphasizes the technological<br />readiness of waveguide-based NbN HEB mixers employing<br />a GaN buffer-layer
